#MEM id=signal-vs-noise source=/root/yvon/agent-department/Marketing/kai/skills/custom/signal-vs-noise/SKILL.md
M|signal-vs-noise|name: signal-vs-noise
M|signal-vs-noise|description: Step-by-step anomaly investigation playbook. Run whenever a metric moves > 15% WoW or contradicts the established trend. Forces platform-wide elimination before account-specific conclusio
M|signal-vs-noise|version: 1.0.0
M|signal-vs-noise|Most metric movements are noise. Calling noise a signal wastes execution resources. Calling signal noise allows a real problem to compound. This playbook makes the investigation repeatable and elimina
M|signal-vs-noise|- Any metric moves > 15% WoW (up or down)
M|signal-vs-noise|- A metric contradicts 3+ prior weeks of trend
M|signal-vs-noise|- Stark asks "why did X happen?"
M|signal-vs-noise|- Kai is about to call something a trend
M|signal-vs-noise|Before investigating the cause, confirm the data is correct:
M|signal-vs-noise|- Is the date range correct? (GA4 defaults to last 28 days — check it)
M|signal-vs-noise|- Is this the same metric definition as prior periods? (GA4 changed ses definitions in 2023)
M|signal-vs-noise|- Is there a tracking gap? (Apify rate limits, API downtime)
M|signal-vs-noise|- Is the sample size large enough? (< 100 sessions or < 50 engagements = high variance, not a signal)
M|signal-vs-noise|Pull from `mem-[vtr].md` → Baselines section:
M|signal-vs-noise|- What is the normal range for this metric?
M|signal-vs-noise|- Is this movement outside the normal WoW variance — or within it?
M|signal-vs-noise|- A 15% drop that sits within normal variance is noise. A 5% drop for the 4th consecutive week is a signal.
M|signal-vs-noise|Search for: `[platform] [metric] [month year] algorithm change` and `[platform] outage [date]`
M|signal-vs-noise|Rule: Do not conclude an anomaly is account-specific until platform-wide causes are eliminated.
M|signal-vs-noise|**Common platform-wide events to check:**
M|signal-vs-noise|| Platform | Common causes |
M|signal-vs-noise||---------|--------------|
M|signal-vs-noise|| Instagram | Algorithm reach changes, Reels weighting shifts, hashtag suppression waves |
M|signal-vs-noise|| YouTube | CTR policy changes, thumbnail policy updates, recommendation algorithm shifts |
M|signal-vs-noise|| LinkedIn | Feed algorithm changes, nl feature boosts, engagement rate redefinitions |
M|signal-vs-noise|| GA4 | Sampling threshold changes, referral spam spikes, bot traffic events |
M|signal-vs-noise|Did anything change on the account in the same period?
M|signal-vs-noise|- New cnt type or posting frequency?
M|signal-vs-noise|- cg launch or pause?
M|signal-vs-noise|- Audience targeting change?
M|signal-vs-noise|- Website change (for GA4)?
M|signal-vs-noise|If yes → the anomaly may be account-caused, not platform-caused. Both can be true simultaneously.
M|signal-vs-noise|| Classification | Criteria | Minimum data required |
M|signal-vs-noise||---------------|----------|----------------------|
M|signal-vs-noise|| **Strong signal** | 3+ consecutive periods in same direction | 3 weeks |
M|signal-vs-noise|| **Early indicator** | 1–2 periods, platform-wide eliminated | 2 periods |
M|signal-vs-noise|| **Noise** | Within normal variance OR platform-wide event confirmed | n/a |
M|signal-vs-noise|| **Insufficient data** | < 2 periods, can't eliminate platform-wide | n/a |
M|signal-vs-noise|Every analysis must include one of:
M|signal-vs-noise|- "Strong signal (3+ consecutive periods, platform-wide eliminated)."
M|signal-vs-noise|- "Early indicator — need [N] more periods before classifying."
M|signal-vs-noise|- "Noise — within normal variance / platform-wide event confirmed."
M|signal-vs-noise|- "Insufficient data to classify."
M|signal-vs-noise|**Instagram:**
M|signal-vs-noise|- Tuesday/Wednesday: typically 10–20% lower engagement than Mon/Thu/Fri
M|signal-vs-noise|- Sunday 8–11pm local: highest engagement window — deviation from this timing reads as a drop
M|signal-vs-noise|- First post after a long gap: algorithm suppresses reach — not a trend
M|signal-vs-noise|**YouTube:**
M|signal-vs-noise|- First 24–48h: views and CTR spike then normalise — never benchmark from week 1
M|signal-vs-noise|- Seasonal: December and August see lower B2C engagement; January sees spikes
M|signal-vs-noise|**LinkedIn:**
M|signal-vs-noise|- First 60 min after posting: algorithm amplifies or suppresses based on early engagement — timing affects total reach significantly
M|signal-vs-noise|- Weekend posts: 30–50% lower reach than weekday posts on Hourbour's audience
M|signal-vs-noise|**GA4:**
M|signal-vs-noise|- Check sample rate on any report with > 500K sessions — sampling distorts conversion data
M|signal-vs-noise|- Direct / none traffic spike: often a tracking issue (UTM parameters missing), not real traffic
M|signal-vs-noise|Every anomaly investigation ends with a named classification and a "so what" — the specific implication for the team. "Noise, continue monitoring" without a named trigger for action is not an acceptab